00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:01.300
And he just kind of laughed.

00:13:01.300 --> 00:13:03.700
He said there is no recipe.

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:05.850
Oh, here's another picture
of the skull just to --

00:13:05.850 --> 00:13:08.090
you know, you can see its fangs
-- his little teeth [laughter].

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:12.350
So I asked my grandpa
for the recipe.

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:14.070
And he was wonderful.

00:13:14.070 --> 00:13:17.180
He took a stab at writing it down.

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:18.830
But when I read through
the recipe --

00:13:18.830 --> 00:13:21.010
he was actually a highly
intelligent man,

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:23.190
but he had a eighth-grade
education, and the recipe

00:13:23.190 --> 00:13:27.240
that I got reflected his grammar
and knowledge of spelling.

00:13:27.240 --> 00:13:29.050
But that was easy to sort out.

00:13:29.050 --> 00:13:31.350 position:56%
What was not easy to sort out was --

00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:34.660
there was so much know-how he
didn't even realize he knew.

00:13:34.660 --> 00:13:37.380
He didn't tell me how much
liquid to put in the pot.

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:38.680
He didn't tell me -- real,

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:43.110
the secret to how good it tasted
was his home-grown vegetables

00:13:43.110 --> 00:13:46.590
and how he prepared
those and canned those.

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:52.920
So I ended up learning how to
interview him for more information,

00:13:52.920 --> 00:13:55.490
how to interview other cooks
that did squirrel mulligan

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:59.620
for more information, and then
how to search through cookbooks

00:13:59.620 --> 00:14:05.050 position:56%
from the time period when he
developed this recipe to learn more.

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:09.230 position:56%
So what I ended up learning from the
process was that, just like primary

00:14:09.230 --> 00:14:11.900
and secondary sources are
great when you're a genealogist

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:14.220
and you're trying to learn
more about your family history,

00:14:14.220 --> 00:14:17.060
it also works for the recipes.

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:20.820
There are so many cookbooks
now that are available.

00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:22.630
It used to be, I think, you know,

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:26.560
30 years ago if you needed old
cookbooks you would have to track

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:29.530
down a reputable bookseller and
have them do searches for you.

00:14:29.530 --> 00:14:32.990
Well, now in the days of the Web,
there's so many of the cookbooks

00:14:32.990 --> 00:14:34.290
that have been digitized.

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:37.330
And the Library of
Congress has digitized some.

00:14:37.330 --> 00:14:39.320 position:56%
There are a lot of sources for that.

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:40.650
They're listed in the book.

00:14:40.650 --> 00:14:43.670
But so if you need a
help on that it's there.

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:49.070
And so to compare a recipe, if
you are missing out on, you know,

00:14:49.070 --> 00:14:51.650
how long do I cook this, how
much liquid do I put in the pot,

00:14:51.650 --> 00:14:55.210
if you compare it with other
squirrel mulligan or soup recipes

00:14:55.210 --> 00:14:59.560
or like my grandpa
actually adapted the recipe

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:00.940
for chicken, thank goodness.

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:03.500
So I was able to look at a
lot of chicken soup recipes

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.150
to figure out what he did.

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:07.640
And then the secondary sources --

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:11.190
food history has just exploded
in the last couple of decades

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:12.490
and they're wonderful sources.

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:17.160
And I found a lot of them
that mentioned squirrel.

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:20.790
Thomas Jefferson --
Damon Lee Fowler worked

00:15:20.790 --> 00:15:22.920
with the early Monticello recipes,,

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:27.690
and Thomas Jefferson had
recipes for squirrel.

00:15:27.690 --> 00:15:30.970
There's so many good
books that I read through.

00:15:30.970 --> 00:15:34.130
Mark Kurlansky wrote <i>Food
From a Younger Land </i>,

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:36.840
and I learned that the
squirrel mulligan recipe

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:40.940
that was my grandfather's
-- that was a regional dish,

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:44.290
fairly close in range to
where my grandparents lived.

00:15:44.290 --> 00:15:47.230
And that it started in the
Golden Age of Railroading.

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:49.940
The hobos would sort of do
these communal one-pot dishes.

00:15:49.940 --> 00:15:52.430
And it's a cousin to
burgoo and booya

00:15:52.430 --> 00:15:54.380
and Brunswick stew
and some other things.

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:57.850
So by understanding
this recipe in context,

00:15:57.850 --> 00:16:00.340
the primary documents help
me sort of narrow down when

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:03.180
and where it came from, but also
how to cook it successfully.

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:07.840
And those secondary sources really
help me to know how my family fit

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:11.670 position:56%
into this culinary history and
social history of the United States.

00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:16.930
So it's fascinating that
recipes can do this for us.

00:16:16.930 --> 00:16:20.610
Every single recipe
you have has a story.

00:16:20.610 --> 00:16:22.190
Some of them may be very boring.

00:16:22.190 --> 00:16:25.060
I think the most boring recipe
story in the world is --

00:16:25.060 --> 00:16:27.100
I clipped this out of
the newspaper last week

00:16:27.100 --> 00:16:29.340
and I haven't made
it yet [laughter].

00:16:29.340 --> 00:16:32.810
But for so many other recipes
that we have in our boxes

00:16:32.810 --> 00:16:36.300
and our card files, there's
a lot of more there to it.

00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:40.420
The story of a recipe is where
it came from if you know that.

00:16:40.420 --> 00:16:41.840
Who used it.

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:43.630
How it was served.

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:45.730
You know, the squirrel
mulligan story.

00:16:45.730 --> 00:16:49.580
You know, I love this serving
it to the new daughter-in-law.

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:51.210
How it changed over time.

00:16:51.210 --> 00:16:53.230
We're going to talk more
about that in a second.

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:54.960
Stories or tales connected to it.

00:16:54.960 --> 00:16:58.870
And then again how it fits
into all that food history.

00:16:58.870 --> 00:17:01.630
So think about that as you
go through the recipes.

00:17:01.630 --> 00:17:04.820
I think a lot of us flip
through family recipes with, no,

00:17:04.820 --> 00:17:06.120
I wouldn't want to make that.

00:17:06.120 --> 00:17:07.420
No, I wouldn't want to eat that.

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:08.890
That's how we look at them.

00:17:08.890 --> 00:17:12.970 position:56%
But if you look at them as what can
this recipe tell me about the people

00:17:12.970 --> 00:17:17.230
who came before me or about the
people that I share my table with,

00:17:17.230 --> 00:17:20.620
then they start to have
a new historic value.

00:17:20.620 --> 00:17:22.850 position:56%
Let me tell you another recipe story

00:17:22.850 --> 00:17:27.330
that will tell you a little
bit more about recipes here.

00:17:27.330 --> 00:17:31.050
This is me back in 2006.

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:33.060
So I got engaged.

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:35.190
And the next year I got married.

00:17:35.190 --> 00:17:39.780
If you'll notice the groom has
an Air Force officer's uniform.

00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:43.930
What that adds up to very
quickly is moving boxes.

00:17:43.930 --> 00:17:45.230
So we got married.

00:17:45.230 --> 00:17:46.750
He deployed the next month.

00:17:46.750 --> 00:17:49.080
A couple of months
later he came back.

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:52.760
And then in the middle of
the summer, when I had a baby

00:17:52.760 --> 00:17:56.140
on the way, he announces that
we're moving to California.

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:59.250
And I had lived in Washington,
D.C. those three months,

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:00.600
but otherwise I had always lived

00:18:00.600 --> 00:18:03.490
within a four-hour
driving distance of home.

00:18:03.490 --> 00:18:07.240
So suddenly I packed up
everything I owned, left everybody

00:18:07.240 --> 00:18:11.780
that I knew except for my
husband, and headed cross-country.

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:13.490
And so really it was
sort of a recipe

00:18:13.490 --> 00:18:17.790
for home sickness is what it was.

00:18:17.790 --> 00:18:21.530
This is a picture -- we ate at
Chez Panisse, if you all know

00:18:21.530 --> 00:18:22.830
that famous restaurant in Berkeley.

00:18:22.830 --> 00:18:24.620
We ate there on our first
wedding anniversary.

00:18:24.620 --> 00:18:27.090
And then the next month
little guy popped up here.

00:18:27.090 --> 00:18:30.650
And I was working on this
book at the same time.

00:18:30.650 --> 00:18:34.930
And what I realized is
the home sickness was

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:37.610
so thick you could almost
grab it out of the air

00:18:37.610 --> 00:18:39.900
and squeeze the juice out of it.

00:18:39.900 --> 00:18:41.710
I missed my mom and dad.

00:18:41.710 --> 00:18:43.510
Especially though when
you're pregnant, you know,

00:18:43.510 --> 00:18:45.490 position:56%
you just really want your mom there.

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:46.790
I missed my brother.

00:18:46.790 --> 00:18:48.610
I missed all that familiarity.

00:18:48.610 --> 00:18:51.610
The first holidays came --
Thanksgiving and Christmas and none

00:18:51.610 --> 00:18:53.620
of the food tasted right.

00:18:53.620 --> 00:18:57.150
I realized one afternoon,
through kind of a veil of tears,

00:18:57.150 --> 00:18:58.840
that what I really wanted

00:18:58.840 --> 00:19:03.910
to help make things right
was my mom's spaghetti.

00:19:03.910 --> 00:19:06.260
Now, if you're of an Italian
descent I would like you

00:19:06.260 --> 00:19:08.340
to just cover your eyes
please and not look at this

00:19:08.340 --> 00:19:12.890
because [laughter] this is in
no way high-brow spaghetti.

00:19:12.890 --> 00:19:16.160 position:56%
But I think that's important because
I think a lot of times the foods

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:20.790
that are dear to us, they aren't
always highfaluting recipes.

00:19:20.790 --> 00:19:22.210
And I think that's fine.

00:19:22.210 --> 00:19:24.870
I think when it comes
to family recipes

00:19:24.870 --> 00:19:27.610
that we can just take our snobbery
and kind of put it to the side

00:19:27.610 --> 00:19:30.490
for a little while and
enjoy what we enjoy.

00:19:30.490 --> 00:19:35.560
So there in my California kitchen
I called my brother several times.

00:19:35.560 --> 00:19:37.720
We both had made the
spaghetti with my mom.

00:19:37.720 --> 00:19:39.020
It wasn't written down anywhere.

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:40.780
And this is what we figured out.

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:45.400
And when I made it this way
it tasted, it tasted right.

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:49.300
But I noticed that my mom -- I
had inherited my mom's skillet,

00:19:49.300 --> 00:19:51.030
but we had one of those
glass cooktops

00:19:51.030 --> 00:19:53.600
and you're not allowed
to put cast-iron on it.

00:19:53.600 --> 00:19:56.470
So I had to substitute
my cast-iron skillet.

00:19:56.470 --> 00:20:00.330
And then I realized my mom,
she would buy these tubes

00:20:00.330 --> 00:20:03.280
of ground beef whenever they went
on sale, and she would slice them

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:04.580
and put them in the freezer.

00:20:04.580 --> 00:20:07.640
And, as a kid, you knew it was
spaghetti night because you'd come

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:09.870
from breakfast and
there'd be this lump

00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:12.180
of beef thawing beside the sink.

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:15.700
Well, I was about to leave
the lump of beef by the side

00:20:15.700 --> 00:20:20.090
of the sink all day the way my mom
did, so I thawed it in a microwave

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:23.010
which didn't exist when
this recipe came about.

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:26.210
So I'm going to kind of hurry
through this because this isn't --

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:27.510
this is something I'd like you

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:30.050
to just get the gist of,
not absorb completely.

00:20:30.050 --> 00:20:33.330
But when I started working with
the recipe further I started

00:20:33.330 --> 00:20:36.750
to realize that, hey, I'm living in
Berkeley, California, foodieville.

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:40.930
I'm going to go for the fresh
and, hey, why not grass-fed bison?

00:20:40.930 --> 00:20:43.170
Why not free-range turkey?

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:45.930
And as I worked my
way through I started

00:20:45.930 --> 00:20:48.440
to realize I was making
all kinds of substitutions

00:20:48.440 --> 00:20:50.540
that my mother didn't
have those choices.

00:20:50.540 --> 00:20:53.260
That Athens, Georgia, it
was a fairly small town

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:56.950
when I was growing up, and the
grocery stores were pathetic.

00:20:56.950 --> 00:20:58.530
There wasn't much choice there.

00:20:58.530 --> 00:21:02.300
It was like yellow onion
or white onion basically.

00:21:02.300 --> 00:21:05.680
But, hey, if you want to see a
happy Georgia girl in Berkeley,

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:07.800
California, who's pregnant
and homesick,

00:21:07.800 --> 00:21:09.860
try finding a Vidalia
onion from Georgia.

00:21:09.860 --> 00:21:14.670
I about did a happy dance
in the grocery store.

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:18.690
One of the things my
pediatrician told me is don't eat

00:21:18.690 --> 00:21:21.720
out of cans while you're pregnant,
which was really a scary thought

00:21:21.720 --> 00:21:24.930
to me that, you know, the lining of
the can would have BPA or whatever.

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:29.840 position:56%
So I made sure to track down --
they have the little sealed cartons.

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:32.630
And then I started, hey, might
as well just use fresh tomatoes,

00:21:32.630 --> 00:21:34.280
and organic and heirloom.

00:21:34.280 --> 00:21:37.600
And I bought the herbs and
put them on the back porch.

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:41.060
They have the new pastas
that are the high fiber

00:21:41.060 --> 00:21:43.540
and they have the lentil flour,
so they've got the protein

00:21:43.540 --> 00:21:47.260
and by the time my son was, you
know, came along and was old enough

00:21:47.260 --> 00:21:49.660
to eat, you know, the
thought of this vermicelli

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:52.860 position:56%
that we always twirled at the family
dinner table, that was not going

00:21:52.860 --> 00:21:54.650
to fly with an 18-month-old.

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:58.600
So, you know, you do the little
bowties so they can pick them up.

00:21:58.600 --> 00:22:01.760
My mom always put a lump
of shortening in the water

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:03.340
to keep it from boiling over.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:07.520 position:56%
And, you know, then we had the whole
trans-free fat thing and then I read

00:22:07.520 --> 00:22:10.260
that you're not even supposed
to put anything in the water

00:22:10.260 --> 00:22:12.690
because then the pasta
doesn't stick.

00:22:12.690 --> 00:22:16.310
And so I think you can see what's
going to happen with this recipe

00:22:16.310 --> 00:22:20.170
that after a while we wonder is
it even mom's spaghetti anymore?

00:22:20.170 --> 00:22:23.270
There's all these changes.

00:22:23.270 --> 00:22:29.650
But it's fascinating when you stop
to look at why all these changes.

00:22:29.650 --> 00:22:31.710
It's because technology changed.

00:22:31.710 --> 00:22:34.350
You know, the glass cooktop
and the microwave oven

00:22:34.350 --> 00:22:36.340
and the nonstick cookware.

00:22:36.340 --> 00:22:38.500
The ingredient availability is --

00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:42.750
it really shows where our culture
has gone in the last 25 years

00:22:42.750 --> 00:22:45.210
that there's all these
fancy things available.

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:48.400
The things we know about health
and the decisions now that --

00:22:48.400 --> 00:22:52.000
I don't think my mom ever made
any decision of to put something

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:55.480 position:56%
in the grocery cart depending on
how it would affect the environment.

00:22:55.480 --> 00:22:57.110
And I do. I care.

00:22:57.110 --> 00:22:59.300
She would have cared, too.

00:22:59.300 --> 00:23:01.780
But it wasn't, you know,
it wasn't an issue then.

00:23:01.780 --> 00:23:03.950
How much time we have available.

00:23:03.950 --> 00:23:05.670
Our needs and preferences.

00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:11.360
So all those things are part
of the story of that recipe.

00:23:11.360 --> 00:23:13.590
And, unfortunately, I think
that halts a lot of people

00:23:13.590 --> 00:23:16.180
because they think, well, I
don't do it the way my mom did,

00:23:16.180 --> 00:23:19.010
so I don't even know which
is the real family recipe.

00:23:19.010 --> 00:23:22.070
Well, the answer is they're
both the real family recipe.

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:26.560 position:56%
And the changes between them, if you
take the time to sort of explain,

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:29.950
is a fascinating trail
for future generations

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:32.210
to read about how life changed.

00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:35.330
I mean, this was just,
you know, one generation.

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:37.920
So let's look at some
other recipes to kind

00:23:37.920 --> 00:23:41.300
of see what historical
trails are inside them.

00:23:41.300 --> 00:23:43.320
This is -- I've got these written

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:46.110
down so I know sometimes
it can be hard to see.

00:23:46.110 --> 00:23:48.870
So if you wouldn't mind
passing those along.

