I know it was hard
to tell sometimes.

00:25:36.910 --> 00:25:38.850
Some of these questions
you can ask yourself

00:25:38.850 --> 00:25:42.050
and you can't maybe not come
up with a clear conclusion

00:25:42.050 --> 00:25:45.970 position:56%
until you've read some more sources.

00:25:45.970 --> 00:25:48.170
This is actually a pretty every --

00:25:48.170 --> 00:25:50.250
would have been used for
an everyday occasion.

00:25:50.250 --> 00:25:53.060
This is yesteryear's crockpot.

00:25:53.060 --> 00:25:55.960
If it's hog-killing
time and the lady

00:25:55.960 --> 00:25:59.650
of the house has her hands full,
you know, she doesn't have time

00:25:59.650 --> 00:26:03.900
to cook a full meal and, you
know, help scald the hog.

00:26:03.900 --> 00:26:10.200
So this would have been put on
-- I made my little example here.

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:15.090
If you do a image search
on the Web for pudding bag,

00:26:15.090 --> 00:26:16.730
you will see something
that looks more elegant

00:26:16.730 --> 00:26:18.250
than what I was able to do.

00:26:18.250 --> 00:26:22.000
This is one of those things, you
know, where -- there's Pinterest.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:23.860
You see an idea and then
when you actually do it,

00:26:23.860 --> 00:26:25.310
it's much harder than it looks.

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:27.610 position:56%
This is one of those kind of things.

00:26:27.610 --> 00:26:30.510
But they would have
put the ingredients --

00:26:30.510 --> 00:26:32.300
the milk and the eggs

00:26:32.300 --> 00:26:36.280
and the molasses would have been
put inside fabric like this.

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:39.440
Sometimes it was buttered and
floured, and sometimes it wasn't.

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:41.740
And it was gathered
and tied with twine.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.280
And then this whole thing
would have been set in a pot

00:26:44.280 --> 00:26:47.120
of boiling water over the hearth.

00:26:47.120 --> 00:26:49.710
And so the lady of the house would
have had to just come in once

00:26:49.710 --> 00:26:51.520
or twice just to bank the fire,

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:54.140
make sure that it was
bubbling along nicely,

00:26:54.140 --> 00:26:56.440
and then would have been
able to lift this out.

00:26:56.440 --> 00:26:59.270
And it would have been solid by
then and she would slice it up

00:26:59.270 --> 00:27:01.670
and everybody would
have had a slice.

00:27:01.670 --> 00:27:04.240
But one of the things that
they're eluding to, the trouble.

00:27:04.240 --> 00:27:07.260
If you tie it too tight
then the cornmeal's pulls

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:09.750
in liquid from the outside.

00:27:09.750 --> 00:27:11.050
It would burst it.

00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:16.400 position:56%
So you come in from the field hungry
and what you have is a burst bag

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:18.240
and everything is floating
around in water

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:22.570
and you can't even just put the
kids in the car and go to McDonalds

00:27:22.570 --> 00:27:25.670
because it doesn't exist yet.

00:27:25.670 --> 00:27:29.210
And a gill, by the way, was
four ounces or a half cup.

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:32.730
So, again, that's one of the clues
to this recipe that it's older,

00:27:32.730 --> 00:27:35.960
is it -- there's an
unusual measurement there.

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:38.750
Let's jump a little bit up in time.

00:27:38.750 --> 00:27:43.610
Anybody want to hazard a guess for
eggless, milkless, butterless cake?

00:27:43.610 --> 00:27:46.810
&gt;&gt; World War II I'd say.

00:27:46.810 --> 00:27:48.110
&gt;&gt; Valerie Frey: That -- as --

00:27:48.110 --> 00:27:49.410
I always thought it
was just World War II.

00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:52.140
It's actually -- this recipe
was a World War I recipe

00:27:52.140 --> 00:27:53.740
which was a surprise for me.

00:27:53.740 --> 00:27:56.820
But it had a big resurgence
during the Great Depression

00:27:56.820 --> 00:27:58.520
and during World War II.

00:27:58.520 --> 00:28:01.080
When you didn't have to
use eggs, milk, and butter,

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:06.400
you saved ration coupons and
also saved expensive ingredients.

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:08.740
So is it in standard recipe format?

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:11.190
It is. We've reached that,

00:28:11.190 --> 00:28:14.370
that period where that's
becoming more common.

00:28:14.370 --> 00:28:18.580
Are they ingredients that you
could have gotten off the farm?

00:28:18.580 --> 00:28:19.880
&gt;&gt; No.

00:28:19.880 --> 00:28:21.180
&gt;&gt; Valerie Frey: Not anymore.

00:28:21.180 --> 00:28:22.480
We're reaching that age.

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:24.220
Probably 20 or 30 years before,

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:27.340 position:56%
some of these ingredients would have
been really rare and hard to get.

00:28:27.340 --> 00:28:30.980
And this would have been a super
fancy item to make for company.

00:28:30.980 --> 00:28:33.430
But we've reached the age
where nutmeg and cinnamon,

00:28:33.430 --> 00:28:36.580
they were coming from a long
way away around the world,

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:38.030
but they were becoming more common.

00:28:38.030 --> 00:28:43.050 position:56%
You could get them in the, you
know, the grocery store or whatever.

00:28:43.050 --> 00:28:44.350
No, they wouldn't have
had a grocery, but a --

00:28:44.350 --> 00:28:49.110
I want to say trading post,
but that's not the right word.

00:28:49.110 --> 00:28:52.490
Just your general store
would have had these items.

00:28:52.490 --> 00:28:55.810
Another clue if you're -- you
know, if you found this recipe

00:28:55.810 --> 00:28:59.360
in a family recipe trove and
you didn't have any indication

00:28:59.360 --> 00:29:03.970
of where it came from, the
seeded raisins is one indication.

00:29:03.970 --> 00:29:09.020
Older recipes would tell you to
use the seeded raisins or seedless.

00:29:09.020 --> 00:29:10.760
Seedless came later.

00:29:10.760 --> 00:29:14.710
And seeded raisins -- I actually
found a recipe not long ago

00:29:14.710 --> 00:29:18.890
to tell you if -- let's
see, it was a 1909 cookbook

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:20.190
that told how you did that.

00:29:20.190 --> 00:29:21.610
And you soaked the raisins and then

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:25.460
with a knife you would slit each
raisin and pick out the seeds.

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:27.750
So my father's -- it's
also a recipe you only make

00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:29.050
for people you like [laughter].

00:29:29.050 --> 00:29:31.970
It would have been a lot of work.

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:39.770
And then the citron is
an ingredient that --

00:29:39.770 --> 00:29:43.140
it was very popular in
cookbooks in the 1800s.

00:29:43.140 --> 00:29:47.080
And it's a citrus fruit, but you
use the rind instead of the pulp.

00:29:47.080 --> 00:29:50.760
And now we see it really only once
a year, and about this time of year

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:53.000
when all the fruitcake
materials pop up.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:56.290
You find it in little tubs now and
it's already been candied for you.

00:29:56.290 --> 00:30:00.040
And that's really the only
time we see citron anymore.

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:04.590
Ingredients come and go in terms
of popularity just like, you know,

00:30:04.590 --> 00:30:07.900
recipes come and go or, you know,
the fondue pot that was so popular

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:11.180
in the '70s, you know,
went the way of the dodo.

00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:12.820
But now it's had a resurgence.

00:30:12.820 --> 00:30:15.760
I think a lot of people
are doing fondue again.

00:30:17.290 --> 00:30:18.590
All right.

00:30:18.590 --> 00:30:19.890
We'll jump up one more time.

00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:23.650
Anybody want to guess where
Sock It to Me Cake, what decade

00:30:23.650 --> 00:30:26.140
or so that might have been from?

00:30:26.140 --> 00:30:27.440
&gt;&gt; The [inaudible].

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:28.740
&gt;&gt; Valerie Frey: Yeah.

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:33.010
That's <i>Laugh-In </i>in the 1960s
had that as their catch-phrase.

00:30:33.010 --> 00:30:34.560
It was fascinating.

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:36.920
When I searched for Sock It
to me Cake the first time,

00:30:36.920 --> 00:30:38.560
I didn't find much about it.

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:42.410
And then last week I talked to
the Southern Festival of Books,

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:46.430
and I met Anne Bern who's -- she's
the Cake Doctor who does the books

00:30:46.430 --> 00:30:48.860
where you work on the cake mixes.

00:30:48.860 --> 00:30:50.920
She has a new book
called, <i>American Cakes </i>.

00:30:50.920 --> 00:30:54.190
so if you love food history,
this is a beautiful book.

00:30:54.190 --> 00:30:57.490
And she really tested
those recipes so they're --

00:30:57.490 --> 00:30:59.640
and she had a selection
of cakes for us to try,

00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:01.090
so I know that they're good.

00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:03.900
But she has a little sidebar
about Sock It to Me Cake.

00:31:03.900 --> 00:31:07.970
And I discovered that it started
in Texas and kind of circulated

00:31:07.970 --> 00:31:11.730
through Oklahoma, so the fact that
my Arkansas grandmother had it

00:31:11.730 --> 00:31:15.650
in her cookbook makes sense, how
very close they are geographically.

00:31:15.650 --> 00:31:18.550
But I did find out that
later on Duncan Hines put it

00:31:18.550 --> 00:31:20.620
on one of their cake mix boxes.

00:31:20.620 --> 00:31:22.870 position:56%
But the recipe's a little different.

00:31:22.870 --> 00:31:24.330
And I brought that for you --

00:31:24.330 --> 00:31:25.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] much the same though.

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:27.460
I used to make the Sock It to Me --

00:31:27.460 --> 00:31:28.760 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Valerie Frey: Did you [laughter]?

00:31:28.760 --> 00:31:31.230
I printed it up for you here.

00:31:31.230 --> 00:31:33.070
A lot of times people ask me sort

00:31:33.070 --> 00:31:37.640
of what my ideal format
would be for recipes.

00:31:37.640 --> 00:31:41.410
So I did the Sock It to Me
Cake that way so you could see

00:31:41.410 --> 00:31:43.890
where I've done, you know,
put it in the standard format

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:45.400
with the ingredients listed first,

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:47.270
because the way my
grandmother had it here --

00:31:47.270 --> 00:31:48.870
I mean, that's the whole recipe,

00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:51.750
so people have always asked
me, wait, what do you do?

00:31:51.750 --> 00:31:53.080
So I looked it up.

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:56.880
I looked through all the -- and
came up with directions for it.

00:31:56.880 --> 00:32:00.140
I love doing them in steps --
one, two, three, four, five,

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:03.120
so if I get interrupted I
remember what step to go back to.

00:32:03.120 --> 00:32:05.160
I always put cooking
notes and history notes.

00:32:05.160 --> 00:32:08.790
And then, if I can, I'll put a
little image of the original recipe

00:32:08.790 --> 00:32:10.360
so that the handwriting's there.

00:32:10.360 --> 00:32:11.950
And here's a picture of my grandma.

00:32:11.950 --> 00:32:17.030
So I'll have that for you today
as sort of a template on things.

00:32:17.030 --> 00:32:21.470
So this one is no longer in
your standard recipe format,

00:32:21.470 --> 00:32:24.600
but is it unusual ingredients?

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:27.840
Not very common for the 1960s.

00:32:27.840 --> 00:32:30.160
Any grocery store, even a
little country grocery store

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:32.360
like my grandma had,
would have worked.

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:34.470
Is it fancy?

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:37.120
Not particularly.

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:40.160
You know, I could see making
it for when company comes

00:32:40.160 --> 00:32:43.970
but it would have been very easy
and quick and cheap to make.

00:32:43.970 --> 00:32:46.570
It is very mid-century.

00:32:46.570 --> 00:32:50.580 position:56%
You know, we looked at that Eggless,
Milkless, Butterless Cake recipe

00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:53.210
that would have been scratch and
you'd have done the whole thing.

00:32:53.210 --> 00:32:56.120
Well, by the time you get to
the middle of the 20th century,

00:32:56.120 --> 00:32:59.700 position:56%
you know, get the lady out of the
kitchen, make things quick and easy,

00:32:59.700 --> 00:33:02.110
just doctor up a cake mix.

00:33:02.110 --> 00:33:04.610
That's a lot of the recipes
that I was left with,

00:33:04.610 --> 00:33:05.960
are those kind of recipes.

00:33:05.960 --> 00:33:08.570 position:56%
And it's not the way I cook anymore.

00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:13.030 position:56%
So when I've made Sock It to Me Cake
I have a favorite yellow cake recipe

00:33:13.030 --> 00:33:15.900
that's from scratch, and
then I make that and go

00:33:15.900 --> 00:33:18.090
on with the rest of it from there.

00:33:18.090 --> 00:33:21.300
So with these old family recipes
you can go those directions.

00:33:21.300 --> 00:33:25.520
If it's fancy, you can,
you know, swap a --

00:33:25.520 --> 00:33:27.330
instead of mush make
your own mushroom sauce,

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:29.630
you can put in a can
of mushroom soup.

00:33:29.630 --> 00:33:32.780
Or you can go the other
direction and go fresh with it.

00:33:32.780 --> 00:33:38.130
The main thing is to play with it
and enjoy it and have fun with it.

00:33:38.130 --> 00:33:41.070
So let's talk -- I'm going to
switch gears on you a little bit

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:43.160
and just talk about some
of the things that I notice

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:44.850
when people worked
with family recipes,

00:33:44.850 --> 00:33:47.250
the things that I heard
over and over again.

00:33:47.250 --> 00:33:48.900
That they would be
excited about them

00:33:48.900 --> 00:33:50.680
but then they wouldn't
end up working with them.

00:33:50.680 --> 00:33:51.980
Well, why?

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:53.590 position:56%
What can we do to get you past that?

00:33:53.590 --> 00:33:56.630 position:56%
One of the things I heard a lot is
that the old recipes are out of date

00:33:56.630 --> 00:33:58.730
and nobody wants them anymore.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:03.220
And, as we just talked about,
please play with those recipes.

00:34:03.220 --> 00:34:05.330
If you are a from-scratch person,

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:08.930
and it has a cake mix,
you can get around that.

00:34:08.930 --> 00:34:13.050
You would record the original in
its original format so that any,

00:34:13.050 --> 00:34:15.150
anybody else wants to
play with that recipe,

00:34:15.150 --> 00:34:17.220
they can go back to the original.

00:34:17.220 --> 00:34:18.930
But make your own version.

00:34:18.930 --> 00:34:22.260
I type all mine into the
computer and so I just hit Save As

00:34:22.260 --> 00:34:26.830
and then I go to town using other
cookbooks, using other recipes

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:30.630
for ideas, and testing it,
tweaking it until it's something

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:33.110
that really fits my
needs and my purposes.

00:34:33.110 --> 00:34:34.730
I lighten up a lot of things.

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:36.600
I go fresh with a lot of things.

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:40.150
But they're still those
original recipes.

00:34:40.150 --> 00:34:43.150
Another thing I've heard is that,
you know, how many great cooks

00:34:43.150 --> 00:34:44.830
or great recipes in our family?

00:34:44.830 --> 00:34:47.120
And I think that's
kind of true for me.

00:34:47.120 --> 00:34:49.580
I mean, that chess tarts
recipe that was one

00:34:49.580 --> 00:34:52.080
of my absolute favorites
is Betty Crocker.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:54.140
My mom may have put
her own twist on it,

00:34:54.140 --> 00:34:55.910
but it started with Betty Crocker.

00:34:55.910 --> 00:34:57.220
And that's okay.

00:34:57.220 --> 00:35:00.000
Not everybody has the Italian
grandmother who knows how

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.320
to do things from the old country.

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:04.210
You take what you have
and you play with it

00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:06.790
and you make it into
something special.

00:35:06.790 --> 00:35:09.860
But it's still grounded
in those original roots.

00:35:09.860 --> 00:35:12.430
One of the things that -- I worked

00:35:12.430 --> 00:35:14.880
with my great-great-grandmother's
teacake recipe a lot,

00:35:14.880 --> 00:35:18.780
and when I first made it, my
family didn't like it very much.

00:35:18.780 --> 00:35:21.670
They're a very crisp cookie
and there's no extract

00:35:21.670 --> 00:35:26.010
and they basically -- they're
very shortbread-like in a way.

00:35:26.010 --> 00:35:30.260
You just taste the flour and
it was made with shortening.

00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:32.580
So it didn't even have that
buttery taste like shortbread.

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:33.880
So I played with it a bit.

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:35.320
I took out a little
bit of the flour.

00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:39.490
I reduced the baking time and the
baking temperature a little bit

00:35:39.490 --> 00:35:43.500
until we got this wonderful
cookie that -- with the --

00:35:43.500 --> 00:35:47.190
a little bit of lemon
or orange extract.

00:35:47.190 --> 00:35:50.380
They're mild and they hold
their shape wonderfully.

00:35:50.380 --> 00:35:53.700
So when you make them with those
-- these intricate cookie-cutters,

00:35:53.700 --> 00:35:55.000
you don't have to chill the dough.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:56.300
You just do it.

00:35:56.300 --> 00:35:58.140
And that recipe is in
the book, by the way.

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:01.440
So it's become a favorite
recipe because I played with it.

00:36:01.440 --> 00:36:04.640
And by the way, I included
this photograph.

00:36:04.640 --> 00:36:06.870
I love this cookie-cutter
because of the button shape

00:36:06.870 --> 00:36:08.800
and so I ordered them online.

00:36:08.800 --> 00:36:10.230
And when they arrived I realized

00:36:10.230 --> 00:36:13.140
that they had been
printed on a 3D printer.

00:36:13.140 --> 00:36:15.130
And I thought, this
great-great-grandmother,

00:36:15.130 --> 00:36:19.500
who was born in 1830, could she
have ever pictured, number one,

00:36:19.500 --> 00:36:22.900
this PowerPoint slide with
the picture of her dough,

00:36:22.900 --> 00:36:25.260 position:56%
but this cookie-cutter that was made

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:27.920
on somebody's home
computer and printed 3D?

00:36:27.920 --> 00:36:31.500 position:56%
So sometimes I think that these
recipes, they can travel a long way,

00:36:31.500 --> 00:36:35.760
and they're very flexible and
can do a lot of different things.

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:38.800
Another roadblock I hear
often is either I don't cook

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:42.450
or I don't cook anymore, so I
don't have anything to offer.

00:36:42.450 --> 00:36:46.240
And I would say that
capture the whole foodways

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:48.310
of your family, not just recipes.

00:36:48.310 --> 00:36:52.150
If you don't have a lot of
recipes or there's just a few,

00:36:52.150 --> 00:36:55.600
you can still write about the
things that you are for holidays.

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:58.710
My uncle used to always take
us out for blueberry donuts

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:00.500
and whenever I eat a
blueberry donut I think

00:37:00.500 --> 00:37:03.320
of my uncle even though I
don't think he's ever baked

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:05.100
or cooked a thing in his life.

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:08.980
But in my family cookbook I found
a great recipe for blueberry donuts

00:37:08.980 --> 00:37:12.540
and I credited where it came from,
but that it was in his honor.

00:37:12.540 --> 00:37:14.460
And it has a place in
the family cookbook.

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:17.790
So those family foodways, if
you don't have enough recipes,

00:37:17.790 --> 00:37:19.790 position:56%
you can kind of bring in surrogates.

00:37:19.790 --> 00:37:24.030 position:56%
Don't try to pass them off as
uncle's, you know, blueberry donuts.

00:37:24.030 --> 00:37:26.220
But you can do things in honor.

00:37:26.220 --> 00:37:28.990
Add supplementary materials.

00:37:28.990 --> 00:37:32.560
So stories and photographs and
things to add to those recipes.

00:37:32.560 --> 00:37:36.100
They mean so much more
than just this little bit

00:37:36.100 --> 00:37:37.950
of writing on a card.

00:37:37.950 --> 00:37:39.970
And then there are lots of ways --

00:37:39.970 --> 00:37:43.470
if you're going to go about
collecting recipes, to work either

00:37:43.470 --> 00:37:46.420
by yourself or to work with family.

00:37:46.420 --> 00:37:49.720
And my experience is working
here with the Cookbook Committee

00:37:49.720 --> 00:37:53.130
for the <i>Bicentennial Cookbook</i>
, are mentioned in my book.

00:37:53.130 --> 00:37:57.530
I learned a lot about working as a
group on recipes and testing them

00:37:57.530 --> 00:37:59.950 position:56%
and how that can be very beneficial.

00:37:59.950 --> 00:38:05.580
Another roadblock I hear is getting
recipes together is too hard.

00:38:05.580 --> 00:38:07.290
My recipe stash is a mess.

00:38:07.290 --> 00:38:09.600
And a lot of the people I
interviewed, they would, you know,

00:38:09.600 --> 00:38:11.980
hold out these little
stacks, so they'd be digging

00:38:11.980 --> 00:38:15.660
out of the junk drawer
and behind the microwave.

00:38:15.660 --> 00:38:19.370
It's a challenge to organize
recipes and -- but as an archivist,

00:38:19.370 --> 00:38:23.600
and many of us here are archivists,
organizing papers is our job.

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:28.160
So I gave some hints and clues on
how to go about getting organized.

00:38:28.160 --> 00:38:32.050
Also how to identify which
recipes are heirloom.

00:38:32.050 --> 00:38:35.590
When I looked at things from
my grandmother's generations,

00:38:35.590 --> 00:38:37.550
they each left me a small handful.

00:38:37.550 --> 00:38:40.620
So I saved everything
that they passed on.

00:38:40.620 --> 00:38:44.100
But my mom had a lot of
recipes and whoa be, you know,

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.910
what I leave to my son because
I have shelves and shelves

00:38:46.910 --> 00:38:49.590
of cookbooks and stacks
and stacks of recipes.

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:52.260
So how you sort of
go about identifying

00:38:52.260 --> 00:38:55.630
which ones are really heirloom
recipes you want to pass on.

00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:58.250
And then what's near
and dear to my heart

00:38:58.250 --> 00:39:01.660
in this book is I put my
best archivist tips on how

00:39:01.660 --> 00:39:04.840
to make sure those materials last
as long as possible because a lot

00:39:04.840 --> 00:39:09.030
of people want to save those
things but don't know how to go

00:39:09.030 --> 00:39:12.860
about properly housing them and
what to do to make sure they last.

00:39:12.860 --> 00:39:15.390
So that information is there.

00:39:15.390 --> 00:39:17.170
Another roadblock.

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:20.300
The recipes just don't work for
me the way they did for Grandma.

00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:23.450
And that was one of my biggest
challenges because I'm not a cook

00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:25.580
or a chef in a classic sense.

00:39:25.580 --> 00:39:27.410
I was never trained.

00:39:27.410 --> 00:39:28.740
But I had to learn.

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:32.430
You can clarify a recipe by
adding a little more information,

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:35.200
making sure you know exactly how
much liquid to put in the pot

00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:38.410
or clarifying at what point
you slide it into the oven.

00:39:38.410 --> 00:39:40.930
But then sometimes
you modify a recipe

00:39:40.930 --> 00:39:42.880
like I did with the teacake recipe.

00:39:42.880 --> 00:39:46.000
I have the original version
just as it was worded.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.160
But I also have my version.

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:51.330
So if my son wants to make the
Christmas cookies he always

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:55.220
remember, that he knows
how I modified it.

00:39:55.220 --> 00:39:58.400
So how to research
and adjust a recipe.

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:01.810
I tried to leave a trail of
information that I discovered.

00:40:01.810 --> 00:40:09.320
I also did some appendices to
kind of give learn-by-example.

00:40:09.320 --> 00:40:12.900 position:56%
So I looked at biscuits and how it's
a -- you know, biscuits are simple.

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:14.600
There are just a few ingredients.

00:40:14.600 --> 00:40:16.390
But there's a lot of
ways to adjust them,

00:40:16.390 --> 00:40:18.570
whether you want them taller
or fluffier or whatever.

00:40:18.570 --> 00:40:22.850
So I have an appendix where I
looked in depth at biscuits.

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:26.850
So if you're into biscuit-making
it is the cheat sheet.

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:30.300
You can find a way to
make your perfect biscuit

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:31.600
through that appendix.

00:40:31.600 --> 00:40:35.690
And it's sort of an example of how
you would do that with other foods.

00:40:35.690 --> 00:40:37.480
I also put in information about --

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:40.940
for many of us, if we go very
far back, suddenly we're working

00:40:40.940 --> 00:40:45.480
with recipes from another time
or place, another culture.

00:40:45.480 --> 00:40:46.780
So I had to go about that --

00:40:46.780 --> 00:40:50.450
the finding ingredients and
translating and converting.

00:40:50.450 --> 00:40:53.650
But sometimes it's just
a matter of region.

00:40:53.650 --> 00:40:54.950
When I lived in Berkeley,

00:40:54.950 --> 00:40:58.930
the trouble I had finding a decent
bag of grits was incredible.

00:40:58.930 --> 00:41:01.900
So how you go about finding,
you know, the ingredients

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:04.520
that you really need to
make a recipe happen.

00:41:04.520 --> 00:41:08.710
Another roadblock is the books
in my family don't use recipes,

00:41:08.710 --> 00:41:10.580
so there's nothing to share.

00:41:10.580 --> 00:41:11.880
And that was a tough one with me.

00:41:11.880 --> 00:41:16.480 position:56%
A lot of my Arkansas relatives, they
didn't have anything written down.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:19.620
I've taught at oral history
workshops so I put in a lot

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:21.750
of the information
that I had from there.

00:41:21.750 --> 00:41:23.050
But I learned a lot of tricks.

00:41:23.050 --> 00:41:26.910
One of the things that I realized
early-on is that if you stop them

00:41:26.910 --> 00:41:29.620
to try to make them
measure something,

00:41:29.620 --> 00:41:31.220
it's [inaudible] screws them up.

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:34.170
They can't continue
their cooking process.

00:41:34.170 --> 00:41:36.370
So I figured out to
get an electronic scale

00:41:36.370 --> 00:41:39.220
and weigh everything
and then let them cook

00:41:39.220 --> 00:41:42.010
and then you weigh it
again and do a subtraction,

00:41:42.010 --> 00:41:44.140
you know how much they used.

00:41:44.140 --> 00:41:45.750
That was a big breakthrough for me.

00:41:45.750 --> 00:41:48.260
There were several recipes
that, once I figured that out,

00:41:48.260 --> 00:41:50.570
it suddenly came clear
and were usable.

00:41:50.570 --> 00:41:54.050
So how to interview people,
how to do an interview plan,

00:41:54.050 --> 00:41:58.030
some sample questions on what
to ask, and I also developed,

00:41:58.030 --> 00:42:02.030
with the help of a couple of fellow
cooks, a kind of a checklist.

00:42:02.030 --> 00:42:04.760
If you have a complicated
recipe that's just not working,

00:42:04.760 --> 00:42:08.310
how you go about sort of
narrowing it down to figure

00:42:08.310 --> 00:42:11.600 position:56%
out where the problem spot is in it.

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:12.900
I'm too late.

00:42:12.900 --> 00:42:15.030
All the good family cooks are gone.

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:17.320
And that's one I've heard a lot.

00:42:17.320 --> 00:42:20.840
I put in how to research things.

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:26.420
How to go -- these community
cookbooks are a goldmine.

00:42:26.420 --> 00:42:28.140
And a lot of times
people have written things

00:42:28.140 --> 00:42:31.090
down that you didn't even
know that they had written.

00:42:31.090 --> 00:42:32.820
They've written them
for other people.

00:42:32.820 --> 00:42:35.860
These great old family cooks, a
lot of times they didn't write

00:42:35.860 --> 00:42:37.910
down a recipe because
they knew it by heart.

00:42:37.910 --> 00:42:39.980
They didn't need to
have it written down.

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:43.290
But sometimes they would
write it down for a new bride

00:42:43.290 --> 00:42:45.530
or someone leaving home
for the first time.

00:42:45.530 --> 00:42:48.690
And by knowing ways to track
it down, sometimes you discover

00:42:48.690 --> 00:42:51.680
that those recipes that you
thought were unwritten got written

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:53.650
down at some point
if you can find them.

00:42:53.650 --> 00:43:00.870
I also did some appendices that
help with that, with biscuits.

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:04.630
I researched sort of the origins
of biscuits and how they came about

00:43:04.630 --> 00:43:08.890
and the ingredients that needed
to come together to develop,

00:43:08.890 --> 00:43:12.910
to make those kind of fluffy
baking powder biscuits.

00:43:12.910 --> 00:43:15.930
And then when I was
growing up our --

00:43:15.930 --> 00:43:18.610
my next door neighbor
was a fantastic cook.

00:43:18.610 --> 00:43:20.500
She was Cajun and she
was going to --

00:43:20.500 --> 00:43:22.070 position:56%
she talked often about how she going

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:23.660
to write a cookbook
when she retired.

00:43:23.660 --> 00:43:27.200
And then died of cancer,
and never got there.

00:43:27.200 --> 00:43:30.980
So I interviewed her husband and
her three sons, trying to figure

00:43:30.980 --> 00:43:34.700
out if someone's gone, how do
you pull out some of that legacy?

00:43:34.700 --> 00:43:38.290
How do you make sure that
-- you can't save it all.

00:43:38.290 --> 00:43:39.590
But how do you make sure

00:43:39.590 --> 00:43:42.570
that something is carried
forward to the next generation?

00:43:42.570 --> 00:43:46.730
And I learned a lot
about doing that.

00:43:46.730 --> 00:43:53.690
I don't have time for a big
project is another one I heard.

00:43:53.690 --> 00:43:56.270
So there's one chapter about
sort of different ideas.

00:43:56.270 --> 00:43:59.850
I interviewed a family that they're
scattered across the United States

00:43:59.850 --> 00:44:01.530
and then as far as Saudi, Arabia.

00:44:01.530 --> 00:44:05.020
And they have a cooking blog
where they all have the password

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:07.940
and so they post and they
post pictures and comments

00:44:07.940 --> 00:44:10.070
and then periodically
they print it all out.

00:44:10.070 --> 00:44:12.600
And it's their way of
this scattered family

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:14.360
of sharing these family foodways.

00:44:14.360 --> 00:44:17.470
So there are a lot of neat
ideas now that are out there.

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:21.150
And then I brought
show show and tell.

00:44:21.150 --> 00:44:23.700
It never has to be too elaborate.

00:44:23.700 --> 00:44:26.670
Here's a little cookbook
that somebody made.

00:44:26.670 --> 00:44:31.570
They just typed out the recipes,
sewed it with a sewing machine

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:34.360
to make the binding,
and then cut up a piece

00:44:34.360 --> 00:44:36.970
of a Christmas card for the cover.

00:44:36.970 --> 00:44:39.320
Simple, but a goldmine.

00:44:39.320 --> 00:44:42.180
Here's another one that
somebody did the same thing.

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:45.350
This one, thankfully, they added
a few sentences about the recipe

00:44:45.350 --> 00:44:47.240
which I think is really important.

00:44:47.240 --> 00:44:50.410
And they just punched a hole
in the side, added a ribbon,

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:52.980
and gave it to everybody
for Christmas.

00:44:52.980 --> 00:44:59.400
Here is one -- this is a woman,
that she did this one with --

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:01.950
she had lots of recipes and
then she put it together

00:45:01.950 --> 00:45:05.200
with her favorite quotations
to inspire her grandchildren --

00:45:05.200 --> 00:45:08.390
family stories, took it
to the office supply place

00:45:08.390 --> 00:45:10.500
and had them put a
spiral binding on it.

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:14.710
It's not fancy, it's not
expensive, but it's very effective.

00:45:14.710 --> 00:45:17.840
Then this is my favorite
way to do gift ones.

00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:21.000
I think -- like Snapfish
and Shutterfly, Walgreens,

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:24.680
there's lots of places
that do these photo books.

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:31.620
And by -- you can type out recipes
and print them and turn them

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:33.460
into JPEGs with a scanner.

00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:35.890
Or you can just scan
the original recipe

00:45:35.890 --> 00:45:38.680
so you see the handwriting
and all that.

00:45:38.680 --> 00:45:40.140
Oops, I'm sorry.

00:45:40.140 --> 00:45:43.870
By doing it this way, you
can sort of share copies

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:47.510
of all these family recipes
sort of in all their glory along

00:45:47.510 --> 00:45:52.330
with the photographs and the life
dates and those sorts of things.

00:45:52.330 --> 00:45:56.730
These things, they live on the
server of the photo company

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:59.230
that you're, you know,
working with their software.

00:45:59.230 --> 00:46:01.690
So what I do is I make them
and then I let them sit there,

00:46:01.690 --> 00:46:03.070
and when I know another
gift occasion

00:46:03.070 --> 00:46:06.490
like somebody else is
getting married in the family,

00:46:06.490 --> 00:46:09.460
you can do a Save As on that
website and design, you know,

00:46:09.460 --> 00:46:12.640
like a frontpage for that specific
person and then print it out,

00:46:12.640 --> 00:46:15.620
you know, a new copy
for that new person.

00:46:15.620 --> 00:46:18.890
They also do a lot of sales,
so if I do something like this,

00:46:18.890 --> 00:46:20.840
I'll get it done as early as I can

00:46:20.840 --> 00:46:23.320
and then every week
I check the coupons,

00:46:23.320 --> 00:46:26.490
and when they hit the three-for-one
sale, bing, I order everything

00:46:26.490 --> 00:46:28.470
for Christmas in one fell swoop.

00:46:28.470 --> 00:46:32.610
And then the last thing I
want to share with you --

00:46:32.610 --> 00:46:35.190
this is the cookbook
I made for my son.

00:46:35.190 --> 00:46:38.600 position:56%
We love to cook together and we were
always sort of missing peach season.

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:41.010
We'd come and go and we'd
forget to do the peach recipes.

00:46:41.010 --> 00:46:43.880
So we put it together
in chronological order

00:46:43.880 --> 00:46:45.960
and it's all the recipes.

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:49.370
I had typed them up so I
printed them out on pretty paper

00:46:49.370 --> 00:46:51.510
because it makes it more
interesting for a seven-year-old.

00:46:51.510 --> 00:46:55.170
I did some little photo collages,
again just at the drugstore,

00:46:55.170 --> 00:46:58.550
printed them out, of pictures
of things we cooked and pictures

00:46:58.550 --> 00:47:00.310
of the two of us cooking together.

00:47:00.310 --> 00:47:03.780
But also pictures of the people
where the recipes came from.

00:47:03.780 --> 00:47:07.030
So my son, even though he's seven,
he knows the names of his --

00:47:07.030 --> 00:47:11.230 position:56%
the grandparents he never got to
meet, and knows what they look like.

00:47:11.230 --> 00:47:14.240
He knows what his great
grandparents' names are

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:15.540
and what they look like.

00:47:15.540 --> 00:47:19.050
He's connected to it and he
knows a lot of the special things

00:47:19.050 --> 00:47:22.320
that we've done and where
they've come from over the years.

00:47:22.320 --> 00:47:25.040
And we have a lot of fun
pulling out those same things

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:27.140
at the same time every year.

00:47:27.140 --> 00:47:29.450
It's a easy way to do it.

00:47:29.450 --> 00:47:31.550
I can wipe off if there's
spatters because they're

00:47:31.550 --> 00:47:33.460
in those little plastic sleeves.

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:36.580
And if it ever, you know,
falls into the fire I can print

00:47:36.580 --> 00:47:39.630
out another copy which
is always good to know.

00:47:39.630 --> 00:47:42.880
It can't get lost at time.

00:47:42.880 --> 00:47:45.160
The last roadblock
I'd say is people --

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:49.140
I've heard often said that
nobody is interested but me.

00:47:49.140 --> 00:47:50.640
And I put this as the last one

00:47:50.640 --> 00:47:52.740
because it sort of
comes back on you.

00:47:52.740 --> 00:47:57.570
I think to teach your children,
your nieces, your nephews,

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:00.420
but also the people that are
on the same generation as you.

00:48:00.420 --> 00:48:03.840
The more you talk about food, the
more you talk about family history,

00:48:03.840 --> 00:48:06.050
the more they start to
feel interested in it.

00:48:06.050 --> 00:48:08.490
And even if they feign
indifference now,

00:48:08.490 --> 00:48:11.960
or maybe they are indifferent
now, but as time goes

00:48:11.960 --> 00:48:13.520
on they may become interested.

00:48:13.520 --> 00:48:16.340
I think -- one of the
things I've seen is a lot

00:48:16.340 --> 00:48:18.740
of times people get interested
at about retirement age,

00:48:18.740 --> 00:48:21.220
so right about the time that the
generation before them has all

00:48:21.220 --> 00:48:22.520
died out.

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:24.800
They suddenly think,
I didn't think to ask.

00:48:24.800 --> 00:48:28.620 position:56%
Well, if you save these things,
then the people who come behind you,

00:48:28.620 --> 00:48:30.690
if they didn't think
to ask early enough,

00:48:30.690 --> 00:48:34.540
you've been kind enough
to save things for them.

00:48:34.540 --> 00:48:36.620
The last thing I would say is

00:48:36.620 --> 00:48:40.500
that sometimes you think
there's not a lot out there.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:43.720
When I started this book
I had two recipes from one

00:48:43.720 --> 00:48:45.590
of my great grandmothers.

00:48:45.590 --> 00:48:48.850
And by learning how to do the
research and learning who to ask

00:48:48.850 --> 00:48:51.470
and learning some of
the tricks, I now --

00:48:51.470 --> 00:48:55.570
this recipe that's pictured here is
for uncooked peanut butter fudge.

00:48:55.570 --> 00:48:56.940
My aunt sent it to me.

00:48:56.940 --> 00:48:59.500
I did ask her several
times about family recipes

00:48:59.500 --> 00:49:01.610
and she told me, oh,
I don't have any.

00:49:01.610 --> 00:49:03.920
When my book came out and I
sent her a copy of the book,

00:49:03.920 --> 00:49:05.620
the next week I got
this in the mail.

00:49:05.620 --> 00:49:08.270 position:56%
She said, I knew you wanted recipes.

00:49:08.270 --> 00:49:09.570
I knew I had this.

00:49:09.570 --> 00:49:10.950
But I just didn't connect
it in my head.

00:49:10.950 --> 00:49:14.370
And once I -- she finally
did and sent this.

00:49:14.370 --> 00:49:17.640
Now I have recipes from all
four of my great-grandmothers

00:49:17.640 --> 00:49:19.830
which I would have
thought was impossible

00:49:19.830 --> 00:49:22.850
because they didn't live
for me to meet them.

00:49:22.850 --> 00:49:27.680
But sometimes it is
possible, which is fantastic.

00:49:27.680 --> 00:49:29.610
That was kind of fast.

00:49:29.610 --> 00:49:32.030
So are there any questions
or comments?

00:49:32.030 --> 00:49:34.910
Lots of those people like to tell
me stories which I love, too.

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:36.210
Yeah.

